  "prompt": "Why is the Avanyu an important Apache tribe symbol? What does it mean?",
  "response": "The Avanyu (sometimes spelled Awanyu) is actually a symbol primarily associated with Pueblo Native American cultures, particularly the New Mexico Pueblo peoples, not specifically the Apache tribe. It represents a water serpent or horned serpent that is typically depicted as a zigzag or curved serpentine figure. The symbol is traditionally associated with water, rainfall, lightning, and fertility. It is often found in pottery designs, rock art, and other traditional Native American artistic representations. While important in Pueblo culture, it is not a traditional Apache tribal symbol.",
